The paper deals with the computational complexity of a mobile puzzle game, which is a topic that falls under the scope of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The proof of NP-hardness involves the reduction of Trainyard to a known NP-hard problem, which is a technique commonly used in computational complexity theory and algorithm design, and thus suggests that the paper could also be classified under data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The problem of determining whether there exists a solution to a given Trainyard level involves spatial reasoning and graph traversal, which are topics that are often studied in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves the analysis of the complexity of a game, which is a topic that falls under the scope of computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and game theory (cs.GT).
